<div class="d-panels font-secondary-light">
<div id="aip_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none">
<div class="p" id="A1">
<sup>1</sup>Department of Biomedical Informatics, Columbia University, New York, NY</div>
<div id="A2">
<sup>2</sup>Medical Informatics Services, New York-Presbyterian Hospital, New York, NY</div>
<div id="A3">
<sup>3</sup>Department of Biostatistics, Columbia University, New York, NY</div>
<div class="author-notes p">
<div class="fn" id="CR1">
<sup>#:</sup><p class="display-inline"><strong>Corresponding Author</strong> Chunhua Weng, Department of Biomedical Informatics, Columbia University, 622 West 168th St, PH-20 Room 407, New York, NY 10032, <span>chunhua@columbia.edu</span></p>
</div>
<div class="fn" id="FN1">
<sup>✉</sup><p class="display-inline" id="P1">Contributor and Guarantor Information</p>
<p id="P2">JRR contributed to idea generation, design of the study, data analysis, interpretation of data, drafting the initial manuscript, and manuscript revisions. GH contributed to interpretation of data and manuscript revisions. YKKC contributed to interpretation of data and manuscript revisions. CW contributed to idea generation, design of the study, procurement of data, data analysis, interpretation of data, manuscript revisions, and supervised the research; CW had full access to all the data in the study and takes responsibility for the integrity of the data while JRR takes full responsibility for the accuracy of the data analysis. The corresponding author is the guarantor of the article and attests that all listed authors meet authorship criteria and that no others meeting the criteria have been omitted.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div id="anp_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none"><div class="notes p"><section id="historyarticle-meta1" class="history"><p>Issue date 2021 Jul.</p></section></div></div>
<div id="clp_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none"><div class="p"><a href="/about/copyright/" class="usa-link">PMC Copyright notice</a></div></div>
</div>
<div>PMCID: PMC8260457  NIHMSID: NIHMS1709755  PMID: <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34044156/" class="usa-link">34044156</a>
</div>
<div class="ra xbox p" role="complementary" aria-label="Related or updated information about this article"><div>The publisher's version of this article is available at <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jbi.2021.103822" class="usa-link usa-link--external" data-ga-action="click_feat_suppl" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">J Biomed Inform</a>
</div></div>
</div></section></section><section aria-label="Article content"><section class="body main-article-body"><section class="abstract" id="ABS1"><h2>Abstract</h2>
<section id="S1"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Objective:</h3>
<p id="P3">To present a generalizability assessment method that compares baseline clinical characteristics of trial participants (TP) to potentially eligible (PE) patients as presented in their electronic health record (EHR) data while controlling for clinical setting and recruitment period.</p></section><section id="S2"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Methods:</h3>
<p id="P4">For each clinical trial, a clinical event was defined to identify patients of interest using available EHR data from one clinical setting during the trial’s recruitment timeframe. The trial’s eligibility criteria were then applied and patients were separated into two mutually exclusive groups: (1) TP, which were patients that participated in the trial per trial enrollment data; (2) PE, the remaining patients. The primary outcome was standardized differences in clinical characteristics between TP and PE per trial. A standardized difference was considered prominent if its absolute value was greater than or equal to 0.1. The secondary outcome was the difference in mean propensity scores (PS) between TP and PE per trial, in which the PS represented prediction for a patient to be in the trial. Three diverse trials were selected for illustration: one focused on hepatitis C virus (HCV) patients receiving a liver transplantation; one focused on leukemia patients and lymphoma patients; and one focused on appendicitis patients.</p></section><section id="S3"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Results:</h3>
<p id="P5">For the HCV trial, 43 TP and 83 PE were found, with 61 characteristics evaluated. Prominent differences were found among 69% of characteristics, with a mean PS difference of 0.13. For the leukemia/lymphoma trial, 23 TP and 23 PE were found, with 39 characteristics evaluated. Prominent differences were found among 82% of characteristics, with a mean PS difference of 0.76. For the appendicitis trial, 123 TP and 242 PE were found, with 52 characteristics evaluated. Prominent differences were found among 52% of characteristics, with a mean PS difference of 0.15.</p></section><section id="S4"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Conclusions:</h3>
<p id="P6">Differences in clinical characteristics were observed between TP and PE among all three trials. In two of the three trials, not all of the differences necessarily compromised trial generalizability and subsets of PE could be considered similar to their corresponding TP. In the remaining trial, lack of generalizability appeared present, but may be a result of other factors such as small sample size or site recruitment strategy. These inconsistent findings suggest eligibility criteria alone are sometimes insufficient in defining a target group to generalize to. With caveats in limited scalability, EHR data quality, and lack of patient perspective on trial participation, this generalizability assessment method that incorporates control for temporality and clinical setting promise to better pinpoint clinical patterns and trial considerations.</p></section><section id="kwd-group1" class="kwd-group"><p><strong>Keywords:</strong> Clinical trials (as topic), electronic health records, clinical research informatics, generalizability, evidence-based medicine</p></section></section><section id="S5"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">1. INTRODUCTION</h2>
<p id="P7">Clinical trials are often considered to have high internal validity with strong methodological properties to address relevant clinical research questions, such as randomization to minimize confounding.[<a href="#R1" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R1">1</a>-<a href="#R3" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R3">3</a>] Despite their methodological rigor, a common threat to them is the lack of generalizability, defined as the ability to reasonably apply the conclusions of a trial to relevant patients that were not in the trial.[<a href="#R4" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R4">4</a>] Generalizability is important because it provides guidance as to which patients may find a particular intervention clinically meaningful. For example, gender differences in cardiovascular disease presentation exist, which means suboptimal inclusion of a particular gender may limit the relevance of a trial’s results to that gender.[<a href="#R5" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R5">5</a>-<a href="#R7" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R7">7</a>] Comorbidities, functional status, and adherence to treatment regimens are other example characteristics that can play an important role.[<a href="#R4" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R4">4</a>,<a href="#R8" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R8">8</a>-<a href="#R13" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R13">13</a>]</p>
<p id="P8">There are numerous strategies related to generalizability assessments.[<a href="#R14" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R14">14</a>-<a href="#R16" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R16">16</a>] Perhaps the most common approach is to compare baseline characteristics of those in a trial to those of a relevant cohort. This comparison enables an understanding of what kind of patients are in the trial and if their underlying characteristics (including the presence or absence of such characteristics) can influence the results produced from a trial. This has been explored in many disease domains, with studies finding differences between trial patients and non-trial patients, particularly in comorbidity profiles and age.[<a href="#R9" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R9">9</a>,<a href="#R17" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R17">17</a>-<a href="#R20" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R20">20</a>]</p>
<p id="P9">A more stringent approach is to refine the relevant cohort by applying a clinical trial’s eligibility criteria to a particular pool of patients (e.g., clinical registry) and pursue a comparison between the trial sample and the potentially eligible cohort.[<a href="#R21" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R21">21</a>,<a href="#R22" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R22">22</a>] The use of eligibility criteria is important because it is often considered a mechanism to define which patients may find the trial results most relevant. In particular, criteria can limit potential heterogeneity within the desired patient population in order to better assess an intervention’s effect.[<a href="#R23" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R23">23</a>] Alternatively, some criteria are applied to minimize unnecessary risks that may result from the intervention. Exclusion of pregnant women in order to avoid potential fetal harm is one such criterion, despite certain scenarios in which pregnant women can potentially participate.[<a href="#R24" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R24">24</a>-<a href="#R26" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R26">26</a>] Similar to the aforementioned generalizability studies, application of eligibility has also been explored, with findings of different comorbidity profiles and disease severities observed.[<a href="#R27" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R27">27</a>-<a href="#R32" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R32">32</a>]</p>
<p id="P10">Although there have been many prior explorations comparing a trial sample with a potentially eligible cohort, a prominent limitation in these explorations is their comparisons are between different clinical settings or geographical locations. Specifically, the trial settings are different from the comparator settings. Clinical setting can impact the trial results because individuals in different settings are prone to different healthcare utilization patterns.[<a href="#R13" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R13">13</a>,<a href="#R33" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R33">33</a>] For example, rural areas may be susceptible to less access to cancer screening resources than their urban counterparts, which increases the likelihood of delayed cancer diagnoses and may render a potential treatment strategy less beneficial.[<a href="#R34" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R34">34</a>-<a href="#R36" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R36">36</a>]</p>
<p id="P11">This study aims to build upon the prior generalizability assessment literature by controlling for clinical setting. Additionally, this study has a unique opportunity to address a potential temporality concern for generalizability assessments by focusing on when the trial was ongoing as opposed to when the trial was completed (as is the typical case for most generalizability assessments); this opportunity is worthwhile because it further ensures the patients are subject to the same treatment opportunities (and available medical knowledge) that were available at the time of trial pursuit. Thus, the primary aim of this study is to present a generalizability assessment method that compares clinical profiles of trial participants (TP) to potentially eligible (PE) patients during time of recruitment based on their available electronic health record (EHR) data, with both TP and PE coming from the same clinical environment. PE patients for this study are those that did not participate in the selected trial, but they had the same clinical event of interest of the chosen trial and are approximated to qualify for the trial based on their EHR data. To do so, we examined three diverse trials from one institution, constructed relevant cohorts, and then compared baseline clinical characteristics. Baseline clinical characteristics were defined as demographic, condition, and medication information that are captured in structured EHR data. By controlling for recruitment time, clinical setting, and eligibility criteria, this generalizability assessment method provides a more refined comparator group than prior work. In doing so, we can examine if clinical differences emerge – hypothesizing there will be differences between the two cohorts for each trial – and, if so, explore if these differences meaningfully impact how to interpret the trials.</p></section><section id="S6"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">2. MATERIAL AND METHODS</h2>
<p id="P12">Details on data sources, trials chosen, cohort construction, and analysis are provided below. <a href="#F1" class="usa-link">Figure 1</a> provides a visual schematic of the methods. This study was approved by the Columbia University IRB.</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="F1"><h3 class="obj_head">Figure 1:</h3>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><a class="tileshop" target="_blank" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=8260457_nihms-1709755-f0001.jpg"><img class="graphic zoom-in" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/7875/8260457/d1826c5213a4/nihms-1709755-f0001.jpg" loading="lazy" height="429" width="750" alt="Figure 1:"></a></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/F1/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p id="P50">Overview of study methodology</p></figcaption></figure><section id="S7"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">2.1. Data Sources</h3>
<p id="P13">Three data sources were used for this study: (1) EHR data from Columbia University Irving Medical Center (CUIMC), an academic medical center in New York, New York; (2) an internal report on individual participation statuses in clinical trials conducted at CUIMC, here within referred to as trial enrollment data; and (3) <a href="http://ClinicalTrials.gov" class="usa-link" data-ga-action="click_feat_suppl" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ClinicalTrials.gov</a>. The first data source, EHR data from CUIMC, contains over 4.5 million patient records between October 1985 to March 2020. It is stored in the Observational Medical Outcomes Partnership (OMOP) common data model (CDM) v05 format that is developed and maintained by the Observational Health Data Science and Informatics (OHDSI) collaborative.[<a href="#R37" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R37">37</a>,<a href="#R38" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R38">38</a>] Data elements of focus for this study are those that are stored in a structured database format (i.e., non-free text note data), coming from sources that utilize structured representations (e.g., conditions from encounter records and problem lists, demographics from basic information forms, etc.) The second data source, trial enrollment data, contains data regarding patient medical record number (MRN) that can be linked to the aforementioned EHR data. It also contains trial identifiers, participation status within a trial (e.g., “completed”), and date of status. Finally, <a href="http://ClinicalTrials.gov" class="usa-link" data-ga-action="click_feat_suppl" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ClinicalTrials.gov</a> is a public repository that stores reported characteristics and results of clinical research studies.[<a href="#R39" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R39">39</a>,<a href="#R40" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R40">40</a>] For this study, eligibility criteria was extracted and used for cohort construction.</p></section><section id="S8"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">2.2. Trials</h3>
<p id="P14">We had an available starting set of 297 interventional therapeutic clinical trials (with a total of 4022 trial patients). Therapeutic in this case means at least one treatment arm involved a medication regimen to evaluate. Trial selection from our trial enrollment data was based on EHR data availability, trial sample size, and having eligibility criteria and a cohort entry point that could be reasonably captured in structured EHR data (using a tool called Criteria2Query to guide assessment).[<a href="#R41" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R41">41</a>] Attrition of the trial counts and rationale for selection criteria are provided in <a href="#T1" class="usa-link">Table 1</a>. After applying selection criteria, 34 potential trials remained. Cohort construction is a particularly time-consuming process because identification and implementation of appropriate electronic phenotypes to represent cohort entry points and eligibility requires considerable effort (i.e., searching through literature, choosing a phenotype, converting eligibility criteria concepts to encoded standard data representations, coding the phenotype logic, and verifying the implemented phenotype performs reasonably), so we limited our focus on only a few trials. In doing so, we decided to select trials that are diverse from one another to explore how this generalizability approach may be effected, while also balancing against practical considerations (e.g., number of eligibility criteria to define, if an appropriate index event could be appropriately represented with EHR data, etc.) Below is a brief description of each trial. Throughout, the trials will be referred to by their short description (i.e., labels in italics).</p>
<section class="tw xbox font-sm" id="T1"><h4 class="obj_head">Table 1:</h4>
<div class="caption p"><p id="P55">Attrition table for potential trial selection</p></div>
<div class="tbl-box p" tabindex="0"><table class="content" frame="box" rules="all">
