</div>
<div class="fn" id="TFN2">
<sup>**</sup><p class="display-inline" id="P57">Many trials were excluded because they were either designed to be a small-scale study that typically recruits few patients (e.g., Phase 1) or they were part of a multi-site trial and thus contain data for just one site. For reference, the 75<sup>th</sup> percentile for patient count for the set of 281 trials is 17, so there is minimal flexibility in imposing a higher threshold.</p>
</div>
</div></section><ol id="L4" class="list" style="list-style-type:decimal">
<li><p id="P15"><em>HCV trial:</em> A single site efficacy trial to assess if any reductions in the amount of fibrosis in liver transplant patients with hepatitis C virus (HCV) occur. Data on trial statuses was available for 43 TP for a recruitment period of 41 months.</p></li>
<li><p id="P16"><em>Leukemia/lymphoma trial:</em> A multi-site safety trial comparing two treatment regimens in treatment naive children and adolescents with acute lymphoblastic leukemia (ALL) or lymphoblastic lymphoma. Data on trial statuses was available for 27 TP for a recruitment period of 31 months.</p></li>
<li><p id="P17"><em>Appendicitis trial:</em> A multi-site pragmatic, non-inferiority trial that compares treatment strategies for appendicitis through measurement of patient reported quality of life outcomes. Data on trial statuses was available for 123 TP for a recruitment period of 12 months.</p></li>
</ol></section><section id="S9"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">2.3. Cohort Construction</h3>
<p id="P18">For each trial, two mutually exclusive cohorts were constructed: (1) TP, defined as patients that participated in the trial; and (2) PE, defined as patients who did not participate in the trial but could potentially qualify for the trial based on their EHR data. For the latter cohort, the use of “potentially” is meant to indicate these individuals are approximated to be relevant patients to generalize to because our data is limited, including (1) lack of data on whether or not patients were approached about the trial and/or declined participation, (2) not all eligibility criteria can necessarily be represented in our EHR data, despite our trial selection process, and (3) <a href="http://ClinicalTrials.gov" class="usa-link" data-ga-action="click_feat_suppl" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ClinicalTrials.gov</a> only provides a snapshot of clinical trial protocols, which means additional eligibility criteria information might not be included.[<a href="#R40" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R40">40</a>] Even if all this was captured, patients still need to be double-checked for eligibility in-person before actual trial enrollment, thus lending further credence to the “potentially” moniker.</p>
<p id="P19">For each cohort, entry was predicated on an index event, which was defined as a clinical event that is necessary for trial entry. The index event is meant to define the broadest possible group of patients that might find the trial relevant, while serving as a reference point for applying eligibility criteria. The index event and eligibility criteria were divided into separate steps in order to provide a sense of which criteria might be the most restrictive in identifying relevant patients. For the TP cohort, the index event was cross-checked with the recorded status date from the trial enrollment data to ensure consistent cohort entry – if an inconsistency was observed (i.e., a patient does not qualify for the selected index event relative to the recorded status data), the patient was excluded. For the PE cohort, allowable index dates had to occur between the earliest and latest entry dates of their TP counterparts as per the trial enrollment data, with the earliest date selected for entry. The application of the trial dates to bound allowable entries for the PE cohort was meant to mitigate possible temporal biases in how the EHR data was recorded (e.g., EHR data recorded a decade before the trial start could be susceptible to different coding practices, available treatment strategies, or systems used). Patients could only enter a cohort once. These cohorts are also referred to as starting cohorts.</p>
<p id="P20">After establishing starting cohorts, eligibility criteria were applied to create the final cohorts. Eligibility criteria were extracted from each trial’s <a href="http://ClinicalTrials.gov" class="usa-link" data-ga-action="click_feat_suppl" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ClinicalTrials.gov</a> entry and mapped to assess exclusion, i.e., qualification for a criterion meant disqualification into the final cohorts. If a criterion could not be reasonably captured in our available data, it was not implemented (e.g., “inability to give consent”). For TP, the expectation was that none should qualify for exclusion criteria – however, patients were excluded if they did qualify. When possible, the index event and eligibility criteria were defined by rule-based electronic phenotypes. If a viable phenotype was not found or required additional specification when reasonable, criteria was defined based on details provided from the <a href="http://ClinicalTrials.gov" class="usa-link" data-ga-action="click_feat_suppl" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ClinicalTrials.gov</a> entry and relevant reference materials such as UpToDate and RxNav.[<a href="#R42" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R42">42</a>-<a href="#R44" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R44">44</a>] Brief descriptions of each trial’s index event and exclusion criteria are provided below. Additional details of eligibility mapping, algorithm justification, timing applied, and electronic codes used are provided in <a href="#SD4" class="usa-link">Supplemental Material – Eligibility Criteria Mapping</a>, <strong>01H_Codes, 02L_Codes,</strong> and <strong>03A_Codes</strong>. References for electronic phenotypes (beyond UpToDate and RxNav) are noted where applicable.</p>
<ol id="L6" class="list" style="list-style-type:decimal">
<li><p id="P21"><em>HCV trial:</em> The index event was liver transplantation with a diagnosis of HCV.[<a href="#R45" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R45">45</a>] Exclusion criteria included age less than 18 years old; evidence of human immunodeficiency virus (HIV);[<a href="#R46" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R46">46</a>] hepatitis B virus (HBV) co-infection;[<a href="#R45" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R45">45</a>] enrollment in another trial; females of childbearing age;[<a href="#R47" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R47">47</a>] prior tuberculosis infection;[<a href="#R48" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R48">48</a>] and evidence of Clostridium difficile infection.[<a href="#R49" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R49">49</a>]</p></li>
<li><p id="P22"><em>Leukemia/lymphoma trial:</em> The index event was confirmed diagnosis of ALL or lymphoblastic lymphoma with an age between 1 year to 21 years old.[<a href="#R50" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R50">50</a>] Exclusion criteria included corticosteroid use; prior chemotherapy (with cytarabine as an exception);[<a href="#R50" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R50">50</a>-<a href="#R52" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R52">52</a>] receiving any other investigational agent; evidence of HIV;[<a href="#R46" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R46">46</a>] evidence of pregnancy;[<a href="#R53" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R53">53</a>] and prior malignancy.[<a href="#R54" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R54">54</a>]</p></li>
<li><p id="P23"><em>Appendicitis trial:</em> The index event was diagnosis for acute uncomplicated appendicitis.[<a href="#R55" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R55">55</a>,<a href="#R56" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R56">56</a>] Exclusion criteria included age less than 18 years old; severe sepsis or septic shock;[<a href="#R57" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R57">57</a>] conditions with altered immune response;[<a href="#R56" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R56">56</a>,<a href="#R58" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R58">58</a>] evidence of immunodeficiency;[<a href="#R46" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R46">46</a>,<a href="#R50" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R50">50</a>-<a href="#R52" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R52">52</a>] uncompensated liver failure;[<a href="#R59" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R59">59</a>] medication usage for active inflammatory bowel disease (IBD);[<a href="#R60" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R60">60</a>] malignancy;[<a href="#R54" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R54">54</a>] evidence of pregnancy;[<a href="#R53" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R53">53</a>] concurrent hemodialysis, peritoneal dialysis, or treatment using indwelling venous catheters; placement of surgical device (e.g., pacemaker, joint prosthesis, mechanical valve); evidence of indwelling left ventricular assist device (LVAD); infection that requires treatment with another antibiotic;[<a href="#R61" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R61">61</a>] prior enrollment in study or receiving other investigational agent; and prior abdominal/pelvic surgery.</p></li>
</ol></section><section id="S10"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">2.4. Analysis</h3>
<p id="P24">Descriptive statistics are presented for TP and PE, as per EHR clinical characteristics extracted by the OHDSI FeatureExtraction R package.[<a href="#R62" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R62">62</a>] The features include demographics, medication prescriptions, and various comorbidities. In general, a patient qualified for a characteristic if there was at least one code for that characteristic within the patient’s record 365 days prior to and including the index (codes available upon request). The 365-day timeframe was selected in order to ensure recent characteristics were adequately captured, but also mitigated the possibility of capturing “out-of-date” characteristics that had minimal to no bearing on the patient’s clinical profile at the time of cohort entry. To determine differences between TP and PE for each trial, standardized differences were used as the primary assessment. The standardized difference is calculated as the difference between two means divided by the pooled within-group standard deviation, providing robust analysis in evaluating imbalance of characteristics between groups. A cutoff of an absolute difference greater than or equal to 0.1 was considered prominent, with the largest considered the most prominent.[<a href="#R63" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R63">63</a>,<a href="#R64" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R64">64</a>] We also performed two-sided differences in means/proportions statistical tests with a significance value of 0.05 as a complementary analysis.</p>
<p id="P25">As a secondary analysis, we developed propensity score (PS) models using L2-regularization (i.e., Ridge) for each trial, and then calculated the mean difference in PS between those in TP vs those in PE to provide an aggregate estimate of similarity between them.[<a href="#R65" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R65">65</a>] For this analysis, the PS represents a 0 to 1 predictive probability that a patient participated in the trial, with larger values representing a higher probability of participation. The inputs used were the characteristics found from the primary analysis (excluding those that had no patients qualify in both cohorts and those that had all patients qualify in both cohorts). We chose L2-regularization because we assumed each input will have some nonzero effect on the patient’s probability of participating in the trial, whether it is driven by the patient, treating clinician, or some other factor. Visualizations of the distributions of the PS for each trial are presented. The models and visualizations used the OHDSI CohortMethod R package.[<a href="#R66" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R66">66</a>] All analyses were performed using R v4.0.3.</p></section></section><section id="S11"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">3. RESULTS</h2>
<p id="P26"><a href="#F2" class="usa-link">Figure 2</a> provides an overview of the cohort counts for each trial (<a href="#SD5" class="usa-link">Supplemental Material – eAppendix</a> provides additional information on how the starting PE counts emerged). For the HCV trial, the starting counts were 43 TP and 99 PE and the final counts were 43 TP and 83 PE. Prior enrollment in a trial led to the most exclusions in the PE cohort for 9 patients. For the leukemia/lymphoma trial, the starting counts were 27 TP and 108 PE and the final counts were 23 TP and 23 PE. Prior chemotherapy led to the most exclusions for both cohorts, with 4 excluded for TP and 71 excluded for PE. Finally, the starting counts for the appendicitis trial were 132 TP and 527 PE and the final counts were 123 TP and 242 PE. For TP, uncompensated liver failure excluded the most patients with 3. For PE, age less than 18 years old excluded the most patients with 155.</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="F2"><h3 class="obj_head">Figure 2: Attrition diagram for the cohorts of each trial <sup><a href="#P51" class="usa-link">a</a></sup>.</h3>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><a class="tileshop" target="_blank" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=8260457_nihms-1709755-f0002.jpg"><img class="graphic zoom-in" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/7875/8260457/ad5be14bbd75/nihms-1709755-f0002.jpg" loading="lazy" height="441" width="750" alt="Figure 2:"></a></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/F2/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p id="P51"><sup>a</sup>TP = trial participants; PE = potentially eligible; HCV = hepatitis C virus; HIV = human immunodeficiency virus; HBV = hepatitis B virus; Cdiff = Clostridium difficile infection; ALL = acute lymphoblastic leukemia; IBD = inflammatory bowel disease; LVAD = left ventricular assist device; note that the exclusion reasons are not sequential, meaning that one patient can qualify for multiple exclusions. Details for defining the starting index events and exclusion criteria are provided in <a href="#SD2" class="usa-link">Supplemental Material – Eligibility Criteria Mapping</a>.</p></figcaption></figure><section id="S12"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">3.1. Clinical Characteristics – Demographics and Medications</h3>
<p id="P27"><a href="#T2" class="usa-link">Table 2</a> provides comparisons of demographic and medication characteristics between TP and PE for all three trials. For the HCV trial, TP were found to be older and differ on racial and ethnical make-up as compared to their PE counterparts. Of the 18 medications that had at least one patient with a prescription from either cohort, TP had substantially higher prevalence for 39% (7/18) compared to PE, with the most prominent being antidepressants (46.5% TP vs 27.7% PE); immunosuppressants (69.8% vs 51.8%); and opioids (81.4% vs 66.3%). In contrast, TP had substantially lower prevalence for 22% (4/18) compared to PE, with the most prominent being drugs for obstructive airway diseases (18.6% vs 31.3%); antithrombotic agents (72.1% vs 79.5%); and calcium channel blockers (11.6% vs 16.9%). Per statistical testing, only antidepressants and immunosuppressants were found to be significant. Of note, all patients in both cohorts had antibacterial for systemic use within the past year of their cohort entry. For reference, the mean (SD) number of medications used was 8.44 (2.04) for TP and 7.89 (2.43) for PE while the median (Q1, Q3) number of medications used was 8 (7, 10) for TP and 8 (6, 10) for PE.</p>
<section class="tw xbox font-sm" id="T2"><h4 class="obj_head">Table 2:</h4>
<div class="caption p"><p id="P58">Demographic and medication comparisons between trial participants (TP) and potentially eligible (PE) patients<sup><a href="#TFN3" class="usa-link">a</a></sup></p></div>
<div class="tbl-box p" tabindex="0"><table class="content" frame="box" rules="all">
<colgroup span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
</colgroup>
<thead>
<tr>
<th align="left" valign="middle" rowspan="1" colspan="1"></th>
<th colspan="3" align="center" valign="middle" rowspan="1">HCV trial</th>
<th colspan="3" align="center" valign="middle" rowspan="1">Leukemia/lymphoma trial</th>
<th colspan="3" align="center" valign="middle" rowspan="1">Appendicitis trial</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<th align="center" valign="middle" rowspan="1" colspan="1"></th>
<th align="center" valign="middle" rowspan="1" colspan="1">TP<br>(N = 43)</th>
<th align="center" valign="middle" rowspan="1" colspan="1">PE<br>(N = 83)</th>
<th align="center" valign="middle" rowspan="1" colspan="1">StDiff</th>
<th align="center" valign="middle" rowspan="1" colspan="1">TP<br>(N = 23)</th>
<th align="center" valign="middle" rowspan="1" colspan="1">PE<br>(N = 23)</th>
<th align="center" valign="middle" rowspan="1" colspan="1">StDiff</th>
