<div class="tw-foot p"><div class="fn" id="TFN3">
<sup>a</sup><p class="display-inline" id="P59">TP = trial participants; PE = potentially eligible patients; StDiff = standardized differences; ADHD = Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder; values are presented as either N (%) or mean ± SD; blue highlighted cells refer to covariates that are more prevalent in PE than TP (i.e. standardized difference ≤ −0.1) while orange highlighted cells refer to covariates that more prominent in TP than PE (i.e. standardized difference ≥ 0.1); bolded rows represent characteristics that were statistically significant (p-value ≤ 0.05) when using a difference in proportions test (or means for age)</p>
</div></div></section><p id="P28">For the leukemia/lymphoma trial, TP were found to be younger, more likely to be male, and differ on racial and ethnical make-up compared to their PE counterparts (with proportion of white patients between the two groups, as well as difference in mean age, found to be significant). Of the 15 medications that had at least one patient with a prescription from either cohort, TP had substantially higher prevalence for 20% (3/15) compared to PE: antidepressants (4.3% TP vs 0% PE); antiepileptics (4.3% vs 0%); and antiinflammatory and antirheumatic products (13.0% vs 8.7%). In contrast, TP had substantially lower prevalence for 60% (9/15) compared to PE, with the most prominent being drugs for acid related disorders (0% vs 30.4%); antineoplastic agents (4.3% vs 39.1%); and opioids (4.3% vs 30.4%) – these three medications were the only medications found to be statistically significant between TP and PE. The mean (SD) number of medications used was 1.13 (0.97) for TP and 2.30 (2.67) for PE while the median (Q1, Q3) number of medications used was 1 (0.5, 1.5) for TP and 1 (0, 3.5) for PE.</p>
<p id="P29">For the appendicitis trial, TP were found to be younger and more likely to be Hispanic or Latino as compared to their PE counterparts, with age considered statistically significant. Of the 18 medications that had at least one patient with a prescription from either cohort, TP had substantially higher prevalence for 39% (7/18) compared to PE, with the most prominent being antithrombotic agents (97.6% TP vs 69.0% PE); opioids (97.6% vs 73.1%); and antibacterials for systemic use (85.4% vs 70.7%). In contrast, TP had substantially lower prevalence for 33% (6/18) compared to PE, with the most prominent being lipid modifying agents (0.8% vs 4.5%); beta blocking agents (0.8% vs 4.1%); and antiepileptics (2.4% vs 6.6%). All six medications listed were the only medications found to be statistically significant. The mean (SD) number of medications used was 4.02 (1.30) for TP and 3.42 (2.05) for PE while the median (Q1, Q3) number of medications used was 4 (3, 4) for TP and 4 (2, 5) for PE.</p></section><section id="S13"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">3.2. Clinical Characteristics – Comorbidities</h3>
<p id="P30"><a href="#T3" class="usa-link">Table 3</a> provides comparisons of comorbidities between TP and PE for all three trials. For the HCV trial: Of the 34 comorbidities in which at least one patient was identified from either cohort, TP had substantially higher prevalence for 44% (15/34) compared to PE, with the most prominent being malignant neoplastic disease (76.7% TP vs 61.4% PE); depressive disorder (32.6% vs 19.3%); and heart disease (79.1% vs 66.3%). In contrast, TP had substantially lower prevalence for 32% (11/34) compared to PE, with the most prominent being acute respiratory disease (4.7% vs 21.7%); renal impairment (20.9% vs 36.1%); and pneumonia (18.6% vs 32.5%). Of note, all patients in both cohorts had chronic liver disease, lesion of liver, and HCV. Per statistical testing, only acute respiratory disease was found to be significant. The mean (SD) number of comorbidities was 8.00 (2.34) for TP and 7.78 (3.09) for PE while the median (Q1, Q3) number of comorbidities was 8 (7, 9) for TP and 8 (5, 10) for PE.</p>
