<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/T3/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<div class="tw-foot p"><div class="fn" id="TFN4">
<sup>a</sup><p class="display-inline" id="P61">TP = trial participants; PE = potentially eligible patients; StDiff = standardized differences; values are presented as either N (%) or mean ± SD; blue highlighted cells refer to covariates that are more prevalent in PE than TP (i.e. standardized difference ≤ −0.1) while orange highlighted cells refer to covariates that more prominent in TP than PE (i.e. standardized difference ≥ 0.1) ); bolded rows represent characteristics that were statistically significant (p-value ≤ 0.05) when using a difference in proportions test</p>
</div></div></section><p id="P31">For the leukemia/lymphoma trial: Of the 15 comorbidities in which at least one patient was identified from either cohort, TP had substantially higher prevalence only for hematologic neoplasm as compared to PE (87.0% vs 73.9%). In contrast, TP had substantially lower prevalence for 67% (10/15) compared to PE, with the most prominent being malignant lymphoma (13.0% vs 39.1%); heart disease (0% vs 8.7%); and malignant neoplastic disease (87.0% vs 95.7%). Per statistical testing, only malignant lymphoma was found to be significant. The mean (SD) number of comorbidities was 2.09 (1.00) for TP and 2.70 (0.97) for PE while the median (Q1, Q3) number of comorbidities was 2 (2, 3) for TP and 2 (2, 3) for PE.</p>
<p id="P32">For the appendicitis trial: Of the 25 comorbidities in which at least one patient was identified from either cohort, TP had substantially higher prevalence for 12% (3/25) compared to PE: obesity (10.6% TP vs 4.1% PE); depressive disorder (2.4% vs 0.8%); and attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (0.8% vs 0%). In contrast, TP had substantially lower prevalence for 32% (8/25) compared to PE, with the most prominent being hypertensive disorder (2.4% vs 10.7%); hyperlipidemia (0% vs 5.4%); and visual system disorder (0% vs 3.3%). Per statistical testing, only hypertensive disorder, hyperlipidemia, obesity, and visual system disorder were found to be significant. The mean (SD) number of comorbidities was 0.29 (0.73) for TP and 0.47 (0.92) for PE while the median (Q1, Q3) number of comorbidities was 0 (0, 0) for TP and 0 (0, 1) for PE.</p></section><section id="S14"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">3.3. Aggregated Generalizability Assessment</h3>
<p id="P33"><a href="#F3" class="usa-link">Figures 3</a>-<a href="#F5" class="usa-link">5</a> provide visualizations of the distributions of PS for each cohort in each trial. Some overlap between distributions is present in the HCV trial and the appendicitis trial, suggesting there are similar groups of patients between the two cohorts. In contrast, there is virtually no overlap between distributions for the leukemia/lymphoma trial, suggesting the two groups are quite different per their PS. The mean difference in PS (with standardized difference) for each trial is as follows: for the HCV trial, 0.13 (1.644); for the leukemia/lymphoma trial, 0.76 (5.840); and for the appendicitis trial, 0.15 (1.111). All differences were found to be statistically significant.</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="F3"><h4 class="obj_head">Figure 3: Distribution of propensity scores between trial participants (TP) and potentially eligible (PE) patients for the HCV trial<sup><a href="#P52" class="usa-link">a</a></sup>.</h4>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><a class="tileshop" target="_blank" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=8260457_nihms-1709755-f0003.jpg"><img class="graphic zoom-in" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/7875/8260457/97bc68378a37/nihms-1709755-f0003.jpg" loading="lazy" height="374" width="750" alt="Figure 3:"></a></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/F3/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p id="P52"><sup>a</sup>HCV = hepatitis C virus</p></figcaption></figure><figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="F5"><h4 class="obj_head">Figure 5:</h4>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><a class="tileshop" target="_blank" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=8260457_nihms-1709755-f0005.jpg"><img class="graphic zoom-in" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/7875/8260457/0c62a560ceba/nihms-1709755-f0005.jpg" loading="lazy" height="450" width="899" alt="Figure 5:"></a></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/F5/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p id="P54">Distribution of propensity scores between trial participants (TP) and potentially eligible (PE) patients for the appendicitis trial</p></figcaption></figure></section></section><section id="S15"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">4. DISCUSSION</h2>
<p id="P34">We present a generalizability assessment method that leverages EHR data to compare TP and PE for three trials while controlling for eligibility criteria, clinical setting, and recruitment period. Prior methods tend to use aggregate participant data to compare against a potentially relevant group of patients, which limits these comparisons to characteristics only reported by the trial. In contrast, our method allows for more flexibility in evaluating characteristics, subsequently providing a more comprehensive view of how the groups can differ. Furthermore, our control for variables such as clinical setting reduces potential confounding when making these comparisons. When applying our method to the three selected trials, both similarities and differences were found across an assortment of demographics, conditions, and medications. In some cases, a higher prevalence of certain characteristics was found in TP while in other cases, a higher prevalence of certain characteristics was found in PE.</p>
<p id="P35">Each trial had differing levels of similarities found between their TP and PE. For the HCV trial, the prominence of so few patients being excluded from the PE cohort suggests the eligibility criteria was fairly inclusive. When juxtaposing standardized differences with the statistical testing, only 3 of the 42 differences found were considered significant. Likewise, there existed overlap between the two PS distributions, which arguably demonstrates there is a subgroup of PE that could be considered similar to TP (<a href="#F3" class="usa-link">Figure 3</a>). Regarding the leukemia/lymphoma trial, it had the least similar groups per standardized differences, but this was likely driven by the small sample size, given a difference of one patient was enough to lead to a prominent difference. In contrast, the appendicitis trial had the most similar groups as evidenced by the smallest proportion of prominent standardized differences found. This is perhaps best illustrated by the bimodal PS distribution for the PE in which one portion overlaps with the TP distribution (<a href="#F5" class="usa-link">Figure 5</a>).</p>
<p id="P36">Regarding differences, many were found but their clinical relevance varies. For the HCV trial, when PE had a larger prevalence of a particular characteristic than TP, some differences could be a result of safety concerns for enrolling into the trial (such as renal impairment and pneumonia), but there still existed a non-trivial portion of TP with those characteristics. Conversely, the situations in which TP had a higher prevalence than PE for some characteristics (such as antidepressant use and immunosuppressants) do not readily lend themselves to a systematic exclusion as plenty of PE individuals had those characteristics also. Regarding the leukemia/lymphoma trial, the most striking difference was age, as mean PE age was more than double the mean TP age. This is further confirmed by the PS analysis as age was the primary input driving the separation of the distributions (<a href="#F4" class="usa-link">Figure 4</a>). Although this difference persisted, this might simply be a function of recruitment strategy as this comparison is only for one site of this multi-site trial. For the appendicitis trial, PE were slightly older and had a higher prevalence of hypertension and hyperlipidemia (and thus subsequently higher use of anti-hypertensive medications and lipid modifying agents). These patients may have chosen not to participate given concern that randomization to one particular intervention may have prevented how they wanted to manage their treatment regimen. In contrast, TP had higher use of antithrombotic agents, opioids, and antibacterials for systematic use. These medications are relevant for treatment of appendicitis (e.g., use of opioids for pain management), so potential explanations for this discrepancy include: (1) treatment being recorded later in the record for PE; or (2) some PE having appendicitis, but seeking treatment for a different reason (note that concurrent illness that mandated hospitalization outside of appendicitis was a criterion, but we did not implement it as that criterion was too broad to define, per <a href="#SD1" class="usa-link">Supplemental Material – Eligibility Criteria Mapping</a>).</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="F4"><h3 class="obj_head">Figure 4:</h3>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><a class="tileshop" target="_blank" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=8260457_nihms-1709755-f0004.jpg"><img class="graphic zoom-in" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/7875/8260457/b196d6d57342/nihms-1709755-f0004.jpg" loading="lazy" height="377" width="750" alt="Figure 4:"></a></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/F4/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p id="P53">Distribution of propensity scores between trial participants (TP) and potentially eligible (PE) patients for the leukemia/lymphoma trial</p></figcaption></figure><p id="P37">Despite differences found, the mixed set of observations does not provide a straightforward interpretation between choosing strong generalizability or minimal generalizability as many characteristics had more TP than PE, but there still remained a non-trivial number of PE with that characteristic (and vice versa). What these observations do suggest is that eligibility criteria alone are inconsistent in defining a potential target group to generalize to, despite controlling for institution and temporality. Although the criteria are generally considered as guidance for which patients may find the treatment relevant, their application may only sometimes capture relevant patients and fail to account for other potentially relevant subgroups (or in the most extreme case, not apply to anyone at all). Even with this observation in mind, we did not find any readily apparent systematic pattern in characteristic differences, making it unclear if these differences meaningfully alter the interpretation of these trials for the portion of the PE that differ from TP (with the exception of the leukemia/lymphoma trial, meaning that applying findings to older pediatric patients might be limited).</p>
<p id="P38">A potential strategy to clarify these results would be to examine underlying risks of outcomes. For example, any safety outcomes from these trials could be explored to see if there are differences in risk; however, this strategy would require assurance that the outcomes could be captured accurately in EHR data (which is something we did not consider as it was beyond the scope of our approach). Another strategy is to extend to larger clinical trials that focus on highly prevalent diseases, such as hypertension or hyperlipidemia, to examine how well captured certain subgroups are. This extension may reveal more systematic concerns regarding differences between PE and TP because of the naturally large number of patients that could be assessed, which in turn allows for greater potential of patient heterogeneity. Unfortunately, we were unable to pursue this because we were limited in the trials that we had available. If such a strategy was to be pursued, an important consideration is that many of these trials are usually multi-site trials, meaning that a single-site analysis would only capture a snapshot of the entire trial sample and thus could be a misleading representation of the trial’s overall generalizability.</p>
<p id="P39">The use of single site data is an important aspect to further reflect on. On the one hand, the focus on a single site as performed in this study ensures that patients are from the same healthcare setting, and thus are subject to similar environmental applications such as inherent organizational tendencies or similar access to certain treatment strategies. On the other hand, the results for the PE in the one site may not reflect the characteristics of PE from another site given inherent differences in treatment setting – so although the single site application might better control for some generalizability concerns, it may come at the expense of providing a misleading snapshot of available PE for a different setting that a trial may have had an opportunity to draw from. This consideration is important for the leukemia/lymphoma trial and the appendicitis trial because they were multi-site trials, and thus we might be identifying site specific patterns (e.g., the TP age in the leukemia/lymphoma might actually be a result of a recruitment strategy for our particular site as speculated previously).</p>
<p id="P40">Another important note to make is the challenge of using EHR data for this assessment. Scaling this assessment is currently difficult because the development of these cohorts took a substantial amount of time given the need to ensure appropriate EHR phenotyping for the eligibility criteria. Even with our best effort to select appropriate phenotype representations to minimize misclassifications, we still came across inconsistencies, as evidenced in the leukemia/lymphoma trial and the appendicitis trial. For the former, two inconsistencies observed include: (1) some TP were excluded for prior malignancy and chemotherapy and thus did not qualify for our cohort; and (2) not all patients in both cohorts qualified for malignant neoplastic disease despite this being a cancer trial. For both, this is likely a result of how the index event was defined, which required at least two diagnoses of leukemia or lymphoma within two clinical encounters, as well as use of certain chemotherapies. We setup our analysis to analyze characteristics relative to the start of the first encounter’s start date – i.e., the index date was the start date of the first qualifying encounter – in order to account for prior chemotherapies exclusion criterion (note that some patients still had a record of this in <a href="#T2" class="usa-link">Table 2</a>, either because of the cytarabine exception or because one of the chemotherapies was recorded on the same date). We assumed that while patients could qualify for this phenotype, the expectation is that at the time of the initial visit, a different chemotherapy strategy could be pursued (i.e., a PE having the option to enroll into the trial). Although this strategy provided some assurance in coordinating the phenotype with the trial setup, inconsistencies still occurred. In the case of (1), the chemotherapy or a prior malignancy other than leukemia/lymphoma was recorded earlier than the initial encounter (i.e., an encounter that wouldn’t qualify for the phenotype given a lack of a leukemia/lymphoma diagnosis), and thus led to patient exclusion. In the case of (2) the cancer diagnoses can be recorded after the first encounter’s start date. Additionally, this setup likely led to increased loss in potentially relevant PE patients. For the appendicitis trial, TP exclusions were likely mismatches between what was recorded in their EHR and what study staff evaluated during enrollment – for example, two individuals were disqualified for malignancy in our analysis, but those individuals may have addressed their malignancy such that they could participate. There do exist efforts for exploring more streamlined phenotyping procedures, but translation to heterogeneous data systems remain a challenge to ensure an accurate, scalable, and portable approach.[<a href="#R44" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R44">44</a>,<a href="#R67" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R67">67</a>,<a href="#R68" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R68">68</a>]</p>
<p id="P41">In addition to the phenotyping challenge that limited us to only exploring a small number of trials, there were other limitations to this study. EHR data is susceptible to data quality issues and can thus still result in misclassification.[<a href="#R69" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R69">69</a>] Similarly, the phenotypes used to construct cohorts are limited based on the data sources they are validated on and how we were able to apply them to our data, which can lead to false positives or failing to identify relevant patients. We attempt to ensure confidence in the phenotypes by using TP as a cross-check while striving for minimal misspecification. Relatedly, we could not fully implement all eligibility criteria, which makes our cohorts approximations for TP and PE. Furthermore, we only have data on a patient’s participation in a trial, which means we do not know if a PE patient declined to participate. Finally, some sample sizes were small, and thus just a few patients were enough to impact the standardized difference calculations. We attempted to address this concern by also providing statistical testing as an additional check.</p></section><section id="S16"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">5. CONCLUSION</h2>
<p id="P42">We present a novel method for granular clinical trial generalizability assessment that controls for eligibility criteria, recruitment time, and clinical setting and reports the results of applying this method on identifying the differences in clinical characteristics between a trial cohort and a target cohort across three diverse trials. We found participants differ from potentially eligible patients. The differences in two of the trials may not be detrimental to clinical relevance of the clinical trial results, while the other trial’s difference is primarily driven by age that may be a result of other factors, such as recruitment strategy. Ultimately, caution should be considered when relying solely on eligibility criteria to define a relevant target population as different subgroups of patients can exist, and thus impact the generalizability of a trial’s results to a target population.</p></section><section id="SM1"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Supplementary Material</h2>
